    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2011_Solutions_2011s_page_003_11",
    "text": "It remains to show that if either l = 3 or l is a prime greater than 5, then l occurs at most six times as an element of a triple in S. Note that (p, q,r) ES if and only if q - 4pr = a for some integer a; in particular, since 4pr ≥ 16, this forces q ≥ 5. In particular, q is odd, as then is a, and so q = a- = 1 (mod 8); consequently, one of p,r must equal 2. If r = 2, then 8p = q - a? (q+a) (q-a); since both factors are of the same sign and their sum is the positive number 2q, both factors are positive. Since they are also both even, we have q + a € {2,4,2p, 4p} and so q € {2p + 1, p + 2}. Similarly, if p = 2, then q € {2r + 1,r + 2}. Consequently, l occurs at most twice as many times as there are prime numbers in the list",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
